<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-usage" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Software Usage</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      As mentioned in <xref ref="ch-intro"/>, this book is not intended to be a
      comprehensive guide to <c>knitr</c> or <c>rmarkdown</c>. This chapter
      briefly explains some basic concepts and syntax in both packages and
      points readers to further help resources such as
      <url href="https://stackoverflow.com" visual="stackoverflow.com"/>.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="knitr">
    <title>knitr</title>

    <p>
      The <c>knitr</c> package was designed around the idea of literate
      programming: program code can be intermingled with prose in a source
      document, then extracted, executed, and displayed together with the text
      in the rendered output. The Rmd source explicitly attributes this idea to
      Donald Knuth's <q>Literate Programming</q> (1984). Its basic syntax is
      introduced in <xref ref="r-code"/>.
    </p>

    <p>
      R Markdown is not the only source format supported by <c>knitr</c>. The
      same idea also applies to combinations such as R with LaTeX or HTML, and
      <c>knitr</c> can work with other computing languages such as Python, C++,
      or SQL. The Rmd chapter includes this simple Python-engine example and
      links to the engine documentation at
      <url
        href="http://rmarkdown.rstudio.com/authoring_knitr_engines.html"
        visual="rmarkdown.rstudio.com/authoring_knitr_engines.html"
      />.
    </p>

    <program language="markdown">
      <input>`r ''````{python}
x = 'Hello, Python World!'
print(x.split(' '))
```</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter also notes that Python users may be familiar with IPython or
      Jupyter notebooks (<url href="https://jupyter.org"
      visual="jupyter.org"/>), and that R Markdown notebooks provide a related
      workflow with additional benefits. It also points to the R Notebooks blog
      post at <url href="https://blog.rstudio.org/2016/10/05/r-notebooks/"
      visual="blog.rstudio.org/2016/10/05/r-notebooks/"/>.
    </p>

    <p>
      To show a literal code chunk in a document, the Rmd source demonstrates a
      small inline expression that produces an empty string before the chunk
      header, while wrapping the whole example in four backticks.
    </p>

    <program language="markdown">
      <input>````
`r "\x60r ''\x60"````{r}
# a literal code chunk
```
````</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      After compilation, the inline expression disappears and the visible result
      looks like this.
    </p>

    <program language="markdown">
      <input>`r ""````{r}
# a literal code chunk
```
````</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Normally you do not need to call <c>knitr</c> functions directly when
      compiling a document because <c>rmarkdown</c> calls <c>knitr</c> for you.
      If you only want to knit a source document without converting it further,
      the chapter points readers to <c>knitr::knit()</c>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section xml:id="r-markdown">
    <title>R Markdown</title>

    <p>
      Thanks to R and Pandoc, R Markdown documents can combine computation with
      conversion to a variety of output formats, including HTML, PDF, Word,
      slides, dashboards, and websites. The chapter explains that an R Markdown
      document typically consists of optional YAML metadata followed by the
      document body. The syntax for the document body is introduced in
      <xref ref="ch-components"/>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Metadata is written at the very beginning of the document and is delimited
      by lines containing three dashes.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>---
title: "An R Markdown Document"
author: "Yihui Xie"
---</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Character values are often quoted for safety, and logical values can be
      written with forms such as <c>yes</c>/<c>true</c> and
      <c>no</c>/<c>false</c>.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>link-citations: yes</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter also shows two equivalent ways to write vector values.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>output: ["html_document", "word_document"]</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>output:
  - "html_document"
  - "word_document"</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      List values are written by indenting nested fields two more spaces, as in
      this output-format example.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>output:
  bookdown::gitbook:
    split_by: "section"
    split_bib: no</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      A common mistake is forgetting that indentation. The Rmd chapter contrasts
      the malformed structure below with the correctly indented version that most
      users intend.
    </p>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>output:
html_document:
toc: yes</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>output: null
html_document: null
toc: yes</input>
    </program>

    <program language="yaml">
      <input>output:
  html_document:
    toc: yes</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      The chapter explains that the output format is specified in the
      <c>output</c> field of the YAML metadata, and that users should consult R
      help pages such as <c>?rmarkdown::html_document</c> and
      <c>?bookdown::gitbook</c> for available options.
    </p>

    <p>
      It also includes an inline R expression that enumerates the R Markdown
      output formats currently exported by <c>rmarkdown</c>.
    </p>

    <program language="r">
      <input>knitr::combine_words(
  grep('^[^_]+_(document|presentation)$', ls(asNamespace('rmarkdown')),
       value = TRUE),
  sep = '\n', and = '', before = '- `', after = '`'
)</input>
    </program>

    <p>
      Finally, the chapter notes that many more output formats are available in
      other packages, including <c>bookdown</c>, <c>tufte</c>, <c>rticles</c>,
      <c>flexdashboard</c>, <c>revealjs</c>, and <c>rmdformats</c>.
    </p>
  </section>
</chapter>
